<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <.docs_layout
      current="quickstart"
      toc={[
        {"create-account", "Create your account"},
        {"install-runner", "Install the runner"},
        {"watch-connect", "Watch it connect"},
        {"first-action", "Run your first action"},
        {"connect-llm", "Point your LLM at it"},
        {"workflow", "The workflow we recommend"}
      ]}
    >
      <.docs_header current="quickstart">
        <:dek>
          Zero to your first audited action in about five minutes. You'll install the runner on a
          Linux host, watch it connect, run
          <code class="font-mono text-brand-300">linux.uptime</code>
          — gated by policy, recorded in the audit trail — and then point your LLM at the same
          catalog.
        </:dek>
      </.docs_header>

      <.agent_skill_cta
        class="mt-8"
        skill="install-emisar"
        prompt="Install the emisar runner and verify it connects. First ask me which host to install it on and how you can reach it (local shell, SSH, or something else). My enrollment key: emkey-enroll-… (I can mint one at Connect a runner in the emisar dashboard). Use the install-emisar skill: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AndrewDryga/emisar/main/skills/install-emisar/SKILL.md"
      >
        Or have your coding agent do it — the <code class="text-zinc-300">install-emisar</code>
        skill walks it through this whole page: install, verify, evidence report.
      </.agent_skill_cta>

      <.docs_callout kind={:note} title="Before you start, you need:">
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <.icon name="hero-check" class="mt-1 h-4 w-4 flex-none text-brand-400" />
            <span>
              A Linux host with <strong class="text-zinc-300">systemd</strong>
              — a VM, a cloud instance, or bare metal. (The default installer sets up a systemd
              service; containers work too — see <.link
                navigate={~p"/docs/containers"}
                class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
              >
                Containers &amp; Kubernetes</.link>.)
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <.icon name="hero-check" class="mt-1 h-4 w-4 flex-none text-brand-400" />
            <span><code class="text-zinc-300">sudo</code> on that host.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <.icon name="hero-check" class="mt-1 h-4 w-4 flex-none text-brand-400" />
            <span>
              Outbound HTTPS to <code class="text-zinc-300">emisar.dev:443</code>. The runner
              dials out; nothing listens on the host, so there's no inbound port to open.
            </span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </.docs_callout>

      <.docs_h2 id="create-account">1 · Create your account</.docs_h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Sign up at <.link href={~p"/sign_up"} class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300">/sign_up</.link>. Free covers
        <strong class="text-zinc-300">3 runners and 1 user</strong>
        — no credit card.
      </p>

      <.docs_h2 id="install-runner">2 · Install the runner</.docs_h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        In the dashboard, click <strong>Connect a runner</strong>. emisar shows a one-line command
        carrying a single-use enrollment key
        (<code class="font-mono text-brand-300">emkey-enroll-…</code>, shown <em>once</em>
        — copy it now). Run it on your host:
      </p>
      <.docs_code
        phx-no-format
        label="shell"
        copy_text="curl -sSL https://emisar.dev/install.sh | sudo EMISAR_ENROLLMENT_KEY=emkey-enroll-… EMISAR_URL=https://emisar.dev bash"
      ><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> curl -sSL https://emisar.dev/install.sh \
    | sudo EMISAR_ENROLLMENT_KEY=emkey-enroll-… EMISAR_URL=https://emisar.dev bash</.docs_code>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        The key is single-use, so a copy in your shell history goes stale the moment it's used.
        It's a plain, readable shell script —
        <.link href={~p"/install.sh"} class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300">
          read it first
        </.link>
        if you'd rather, or
        <.link
          href={~p"/trust" <> "#release-integrity"}
          class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          verify the release's provenance + checksum
        </.link>
        before you run it. It:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
          <span>verifies the download's SHA-256;</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
          <span>
            creates a dedicated <code class="font-mono">emisar</code>
            system user and an <code class="font-mono">emisar.service</code>
            systemd unit (<code class="font-mono">Restart=on-failure</code>);
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
          <span>
            bakes the key and URL into <code class="font-mono">/etc/emisar/runner.env</code>;
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
          <span>
            installs the host-matched starter packs (on a typical Linux + systemd host: <code class="font-mono">linux-core</code>, <code class="font-mono">debugging</code>, and <code class="font-mono">systemd-deep</code>);
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
          <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
          <span>starts the service, which dials out to the control plane over WSS.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <.docs_h2 id="watch-connect">3 · Watch it connect</.docs_h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Refresh the dashboard — your host appears under <strong>Runners</strong>, online,
        advertising its action catalog. On the host you can watch the same thing:
      </p>
      <.docs_code phx-no-format label="shell" copy_text="journalctl -u emisar -f"><span class="text-zinc-500">$</span> journalctl -u emisar -f
<span class="text-zinc-500">level=INFO msg="runner online" group=default packs=3 actions=89</span></.docs_code>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        The stock <code class="font-mono">linux-core</code>
        pack is trusted automatically — its bytes match the catalog emisar publishes, so the hash
        auto-pins as trusted. (A <em>custom or edited</em>
        pack lands as <strong class="text-zinc-300">pending</strong>
        instead and waits for one click on the <strong>Packs</strong>
        page before anything can dispatch it. That's the drift guard; you'll meet it the first time
        you change a pack.)
      </p>

      <.docs_h2 id="first-action">4 · Run your first action</.docs_h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        Open the runner, pick <code class="font-mono text-brand-300">linux.uptime</code>, add the
        required <strong>reason</strong>
        (one line — it's logged), and <strong>Dispatch</strong>. The output streams back live:
      </p>
      <.docs_code phx-no-format label="output"> 14:32:07 up 18 days,  4:01,  load average: 0.42, 0.51, 0.48</.docs_code>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <code class="font-mono">linux.uptime</code>
        is <code class="text-brand-300">low</code>
        risk, so the default policy runs it on the spot. A <code class="text-amber-300">high</code>-risk
        action — killing a process, restarting a service — would stop here for a human approval
        instead: same flow, one extra click. Either way the run is now in the searchable cloud
        audit and the runner's hash-chained journal, tagged with your reason.
      </p>

      <.docs_h2 id="connect-llm">5 · Point your LLM at it</.docs_h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        A runner on its own is just a safer way to click buttons. The payoff is handing the catalog
        to a model. In the dashboard open <strong>LLM agents</strong> and pick your client:
        Claude.ai and ChatGPT connect over remote MCP with OAuth, and local clients — Claude Code,
        Cursor, Zed, Copilot CLI, and ten more — use a one-line installer that opens a browser
        approval and writes a scoped key straight into the client's config, so the secret never
        touches your clipboard.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        Now your model gets twelve stable tools and discovers only the packs, actions, and runners
        in scope. Ask it <em>"what's the load on web-01?"</em>
        and it finds <code class="font-mono">linux.uptime</code>, reads its exact schema, then calls <code class="font-mono">run_action</code>; ask it to restart a service and
        that high-risk action stops for your approval. Reads run on policy, mutations are gated,
        every call is audited — and the model never gets a shell. Full walkthrough: <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
          class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >/docs/connect-an-llm</.link>.
      </p>

      <%!-- Optional, secondary to step 5: most clients prompt "allow this tool?"
           per call. Because emisar gates server-side, that client prompt is
           redundant for emisar's tools and safe to silence — the framing the
           agents page uses, repeated here for the public docs/SEO surface. --%>
      <.docs_callout kind={:note} title="Optional: stop the per-tool prompts">
        <p>
          Most clients ask <em>"allow this tool?"</em>
          the first time a model calls one. emisar already gates every action
          <strong class="text-zinc-200">server-side</strong>
          — per-account policy, and human approval on risky ones — so that client prompt is
          redundant for emisar's tools. You can safely tell your client to stop prompting for the
          <code class="font-mono text-brand-300">emisar</code>
          MCP server: it only silences the client's prompt. A risky action still pauses for
          approval at emisar, and an out-of-policy one is still denied — auto-permitting in the
          client never bypasses emisar's gate.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
            <span>
              <strong class="text-zinc-300">Claude Code</strong>
              — add <code class="font-mono text-brand-300">"mcp__emisar__*"</code>
              to <code class="font-mono">permissions.allow</code>
              in <code class="font-mono">~/.claude/settings.json</code>.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
            <span>
              <strong class="text-zinc-300">Gemini CLI</strong>
              — set <code class="font-mono text-brand-300">"trust": true</code>
              on the <code class="font-mono">emisar</code>
              server in <code class="font-mono">~/.gemini/settings.json</code>.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
            <span>
              <strong class="text-zinc-300">Grok CLI</strong>
              — add <code class="font-mono text-brand-300">"MCPTool(emisar__*)"</code>
              to <code class="font-mono">[permission].allow</code>
              in <code class="font-mono">~/.grok/config.toml</code>.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
            <span class="flex-none text-zinc-500">—</span>
            <span>
              <strong class="text-zinc-300">Cursor, Codex CLI</strong>
              — Cursor approves globally through agent auto-run; Codex can trust only emisar with
              <code class="font-mono">default_tools_approval_mode = "approve"</code>
              under <code class="font-mono">[mcp_servers.emisar]</code>. The
              <.link navigate={~p"/app"} class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300">
                LLM agents
              </.link>
              page has the exact per-client steps.
            </span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </.docs_callout>

      <.docs_h2 id="workflow">6 · The workflow we recommend</.docs_h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-400">
        emisar is built for the incident, not the steady state. Use it to
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">investigate fast</strong>
        — let the agent work down the layers through declared, audited reads — and to
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">hot-patch</strong>
        when you have to stop the bleed: a gated, one-approval action that buys you time. What it
        is <em>not</em>
        is your configuration manager. Standing changes an agent makes on a live host are how you
        get drift nobody can reproduce.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        So the durable pattern — the one we'd actually recommend — pairs the agent with your
        infrastructure-as-code:
      </p>
      <ol class="mt-4 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <li>
          The agent <strong class="text-zinc-200">investigates</strong>
          through emisar and finds the root cause — reads run on policy, so this part is unattended
          and on the record.
        </li>
        <li>
          If it's on fire, it <strong class="text-zinc-200">hot-patches</strong>
          through one gated action to contain it — approved by a human, audited.
        </li>
        <li>
          Then it <strong class="text-zinc-200">writes the durable fix as code</strong>
          — Terraform, Ansible, a Kubernetes manifest, whatever your fleet runs — and hands you a
          change you <strong class="text-zinc-200">review and apply</strong>
          through your normal pipeline.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        <strong class="text-zinc-200">Imperative containment, declarative cure</strong>: stop the
        incident now through emisar, codify the cure in IaC you review. The agent never becomes the
        source of truth for your infrastructure — your repo stays that. See it end to end on a real
        incident:
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/use-cases/csi-data-loss"}
          class="text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          the 33-hour wipe
        </.link>
        — investigated through declared actions, contained behind one
        approval, then fixed in a Terraform PR the agent wrote.
      </p>

      <.docs_callout kind={:tip} title="What you just built.">
        A finite, reviewed action catalog sitting between an AI agent and your host — instead of an
        SSH key and a prayer. The model can only call what you declared, risky calls stop for a
        human, secrets are redacted before they leave the box, and there's a searchable audit — with
        a tamper-evident, hash-chained journal on the host — of who ran what, and why.
      </.docs_callout>

      <.docs_callout kind={:warn} title="Runner not showing up?">
        Check <code class="font-mono text-xs">journalctl -u emisar -f</code>
        on the host. The two usual causes are a stale enrollment key (the Connect-a-runner key is
        single-use — mint a fresh one) and an outbound firewall blocking <code class="font-mono">emisar.dev:443</code>.
      </.docs_callout>

      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-3 border-t border-zinc-900 pt-8 text-sm">
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          Connect your LLM <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/action-packs"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          What else can it run? <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
        <.link
          navigate={~p"/docs/security-model"}
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-medium text-brand-400 hover:text-brand-300"
        >
          Is this safe? The security model <.icon name="hero-arrow-right" class="h-3.5 w-3.5" />
        </.link>
      </div>
    </.docs_layout>
  </section>

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
